Etymology 1[edit]

From inter- +‎ cadō (“fall”).

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /inˈter.ki.doː/, [ɪn̪ˈt̪ɛr.kɪ.d̪oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /inˈter.t͡ʃi.do/, [in̪ˈt̪ɛr.t͡ʃi.d̪ɔ]

Verb[edit]

intercidō (present infinitive intercidere, perfect active intercidī); third conjugation, no passive, no supine stem

  1. I fall between.
  2. I occur meanwhile, happen.
  3. I am lost or forgotten, fall to the ground, perish, go to ruin.

Etymology 2[edit]

From inter- +‎ caedō (“cut; strike”).

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /in.terˈkiː.doː/, [ɪn̪.t̪ɛrˈkiː.d̪oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /in.terˈt͡ʃi.do/, [in̪.t̪ɛrˈt͡ʃiː.d̪ɔ]

Verb[edit]

intercīdō (present infinitive intercīdere, perfect active intercīdī, supine intercīsum); third conjugation

  1. I cut or hew up, through, asunder or to pieces; thin out by cutting.
  2. I part, pierce, divide, sever, cut up, mangle, mutilate, destroy.
  3. (of accounts) I mutilate, tamper with, falsify.
